n=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=simanmistrunner>SimanMistrunner</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/21/04 10:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2347.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Grrrrr Robert Jordan Series</span><hr size=1> I am not sure if other folks follow the Robert Jordan's &quot;The Wheel of Time&quot; series, but I have read each of the books in the series up to date.  With the first five or six books, I was captivated by the story and couldn't wait to read more and see how it ended.<br>
<br>
Around the seventh book or so, I started noticing some things.  The guy cannot tie up any loose ends.  Evil characters would apparently be killed only to be brought back in a different form.  It was getting to the point where there were so many unfinished plot threads that I began to realize it might take another 7-8 books to finish the series.<br>
<br>
Perhaps that was his point all along.  His series is continually at or near the top of the NYT best-seller list upon release and perhaps he wants to keep the gravy train going.<br>
<br>
Anyway, the reason for this rant is that I was excited the other day when I saw a new Robert Jordan book out.  A part of me would like to see how this series concludes and I went to check it out.  Much to my dismay I find that he decided he would write a prequel--a book highlighting what happened prior to the first book in the series.  GRRRRRR...  Finish the fricking series before starting on prequels.  <br>
<br>
Anyway, I didn't buy the book and will likely not buy any other books written by him.  Too upset that he can't finish what he started.<br>
<br>
--Siman/Trakon<br>
<br>
